					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rjb-r" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1229263); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1229263&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205701" alt="RJB_R" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1229263)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/rjb-r" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1229263); return false;" >RJB_R</a></span> <span class="odate time_1582348943 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Feb 2020 05:22</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4511705">
									

<p>There’s a lot to like here, an abundance of interesting detail, particularly in the back half, a lot of nice historical flourishes and a dark but not hopeless atmosphere.</p>
<p>However, the supremely technocratic front half as well as how the article really isn’t more than a well-crafted exposition-dump outweighs that for me.</p>
<p>I don’t mind exposition and data but this feels like it forgot to tell a compelling story to go along with that abundance of detail.</p>

							</div>

										<div class="signature">
					<hr class="signature-separator"/>
					

<p><em>Whether you like it or not, history is on our side. We will bury you!</em></p>

